###############################################################################
# <<3>> Gulch layout vaults and subvaults
###############################################################################
# Gulch layouts foreground subvaulting heavily to still feel like an extension
# of V and to avoid the reliable layouts of other portals, with at least three
# different configurations at minimum. Not counting firewood, each map should
# have about 44 normal enemies, with 80% or more being Gulch spawns. Most of
# them should have immediate 5-or-less monster ambushes with weaker guest
# monsters to make use of the entry transient mutations.
# Map types:
# * Standard maps get WEIGHT: 25 and deploy the seven Gulch-unique monsters
#   with lua functions defined earlier in the file, with three different terrain
#   themes shared across each section defined by gulch_boss_theme_sets. They
#   may have a 1/5 chance to deploy one of the four arrangements:
#   * A deathcap ambush with fungal shamblers
#   * Dragon draugr with mongrel wurms
#   * Radroaches with roaming sludgefish
#   * Some ironbound mechanists with rusted inspectors
# * Themed nonstandard maps should have WEIGHT: 15 and reliably present one or
#   two of the above repeatable guest arrangements.
# * Rare guest maps should have WEIGHT: 10 and not overlap in their uses of
#   outside guest monsters- see <<4>> for various potential concepts.
# Layout notes:
#  * By default, each layout uses eight |s and the gulch_loot(_G) function to
#    place thematic loot. When this is split between subvaults, use empty spaces
#    in the subvault definitions and pass the subvault glyphs into that function
#    to properly distribute those rewards- refer to how it's done in layouts
#    like gulch_chambers_river, gulch_winding_coils, and gulch_divide.
#  * With unique tiles for each, some simple wall progression between rock and
#    stone and (bits of metal) from start to finish can easily look nice.
#  * The current gulch_boss_theme_sets(_G) set-up uses ? and ' to place
#    terrain features, with ? using mould patches or stacks of scrap as
#    traversible blocking features and ' rarely being used for deep water that
#    shouldn't produce teleport islands or needs to fly. Keep both of these in
#    mind when placing either.
###############################################################################

default-depth: Gulch

###############################################################################
# The Gulch Onslaught, a chain of subvaults based off of Sewer layouts.
# The outside of each chamber have water, but most of the insides don't.
NAME:     regret_index_gulch_onslaught
WEIGHT:   25
KFEAT:    - = broken_door
KFEAT:    P = mould_patch
SUBST:    - = ++-., ~ = ...WWwx
SUBST:    y : x.., z : x.., Y : x.., Z : x..
SUBVAULT: B : gulch_onslaught_subvault
SUBVAULT: C : gulch_onslaught_subvault
SUBVAULT: D : gulch_onslaught_subvault
: gulch_onslaught(_G, false)
: gulch_loot(_G, "|", 4)
